    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1819-09-16_page01"/>
                
                <p><note>Between 1817 &amp; 1821</note> <note>59</note>
                <note>5)</note></p>
                
                <p> I agree with you that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RileX1">Riley</persName> is beyond the<lb/>
                    truth - but <del>I am glad</del>, liar or not that is<lb/>
                    his affair - I am glad he entertains my<lb/>
                    uncle - and I hope my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtJ1">uncle's</persName> snuffers<lb/>
                    have come to hand &amp; that he is not angry<lb/>
                    with me for sending him such a vulgar<lb/>
                    souvenir -<lb/></p>
                <p>
                    Thank dear little <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxT1">Tom</persName> for remembering<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">Malia</hi> and <hi rend="underline">Jenny</hi> - I admire little<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxJ2" cert="low">John's</persName> performance of his manifold<lb/>
                    duties - I never thought he was little John<lb/>
                    Nobody - he has now proved himself to be<lb/>
                    little John Somebody, and if he stands<lb/>
                    the trial of the new coat &amp; tucker to shirt<lb/>
                    I do not despair of his walking with<lb/>
                    unblenched virtue through the mud=<lb/>
                    -ordeal &amp; vice=ordeal of Navan - worse<lb/>
                    than any fire or water ordeal or any<lb/>
                    burning plough shares on which <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EmmaN1">Q Emma</persName><lb/>
                    or others ever walked ! -<lb/> </p>
                <p>
                    There is said to be some marvellous moral<lb/>
                    or immoral fracas in the Devonshire<lb/>
                    family; but I have not got the story by the<lb/>
                    right end yet - So, for fear of spoiling a<lb/>
                    choice bit of scandal in the telling, shall<lb/>
                    wait till I <hi rend="underline">am perfect</hi> in it - and <choice> 
                    <orig>mean<lb/>
                    time</orig>
                    <reg>meantime</reg>
                    </choice>
                    perhaps you may have it fresh &amp; fresh<lb/>
                    from my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1">mother</persName> - or the newspapers -<lb/></p>
                <p>
                    I am glad <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtS1">Sophy</persName> goes to dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtP1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> P. Ruxton</persName><lb/>
                
                <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1819-09-16_page02"/>
                    Me having deprived her of that visit long sat<lb/>
                    heavy as the night mare on my conscience -<lb/>
                    - To <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GarnX1">Miss Garnett</persName> alias M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Ratcliffe's other sins<lb/>
                    must be a <unclear>alloted</unclear> that of preventing <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtS1">Sophy</persName> from<lb/>
                    seeing the archdeacons pictures! - Well! when<lb/>
                    a person is down in the moral world sins<lb/>
                    enough are always ready to be heaped upon<lb/>
                    Their heads - I think <del>mit</del> Ellen G- is just a<lb/>
                    heroine &amp; <add>hers just</add> <hi rend="underline">a</hi> story fit for the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#AustJ1">author</persName> of <title ref="./Workography.xml#North1"><choice> 
                    <orig>North-<lb/>
                    anger</orig>
                    <reg>Northanger</reg>
                    </choice>
                    Abbey</title> - and no letter in any novel<lb/>
                    was ever better in its own way than <hi rend="underline">hers</hi> -<lb/></p>
                <p>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyE1" cert="medium">Sneyd</persName> and his gout go on finely - Poor<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyM3" cert="medium">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Sneyd E</persName>: as headachy as usual -<lb/>
                    <del><persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1" cert="medium">William</persName> and</del> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> returns to us on <choice> 
                    <orig>Wed=<lb/>
                    nesday</orig>
                    <reg>Wednesday</reg>
                    </choice>
                    - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName> is well - And I have nothing<lb/>
                    more to say - except that I am sorry <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DillR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi><lb/>
                    R. Dillon</persName> &amp; the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#OBeiT1">Bishop</persName> are going to war -<lb/>
                    - But in fact there must be war about<lb/>
                    nonsense in this world. - I wonder that<lb/>
                    anxiety about <persName ref="./Personography.xml#OBeiJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. O OBeirne</persName> does not in<lb/>
                    the bishop's mind swallow up all other<lb/>
                    feelings - I am most sincerely sorry<lb/>
                    for her - Send her <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BailJ1">Miss Bailly's</persName> letter to amuse her.<lb/>
                    As soon as I have my Jewess's letter <add>again</add>you shall<lb/>
                    have it - Adieu dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtM1">Aunt</persName> - What<lb/>
                    pleasure I shall have in being with you<lb/>
                    again - when I have <hi rend="underline">earned</hi> that pleasure -<lb/>
                    - The greatest I think I have now left upon<lb/>
                    earth -<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/></p>
               
            </div>
